<% content_for :title, "Algorithms" %>

<section class="space-y-8">
  <header class="space-y-2">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Algorithms</h1>
    <p class="text-slate-700">
      ML-DSA (FIPS 204) ships in three parameter sets trading signature
      size and speed for security margin. All three are FIPS-approved.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Parameter sets</h2>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-left text-sm border border-slate-200">
        <thead class="bg-slate-50">
          <tr>
            <th class="p-2 border-b">alg (JOSE)</th>
            <th class="p-2 border-b">NIST level</th>
            <th class="p-2 border-b">Public key</th>
            <th class="p-2 border-b">Signature</th>
            <th class="p-2 border-b">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-2 border-b"><code>ML-DSA-44</code></td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">Category 2 (~AES-128)</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">1312 B</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">~2420 B</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">Smallest, fastest; minimum level for new systems.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-2 border-b"><code>ML-DSA-65</code></td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">Category 3 (~AES-192)</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">1952 B</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">~3293 B</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">Recommended default. Balanced.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-2 border-b"><code>ML-DSA-87</code></td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">Category 5 (~AES-256)</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">2592 B</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">~4595 B</td>
            <td class="p-2 border-b">Highest margin; larger tokens on the wire.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-slate-600">
      Sizes are specification-defined, not implementation-specific. All three
      fit comfortably inside typical cookie / header limits for well-formed
      tokens, but ML-DSA-87 headers will blow past default Nginx
      <code>large_client_header_buffers</code> settings — budget for that
      before rolling out.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Which one?</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>ML-DSA-65</strong> for anything new. Category 3 is the
          safe default.</li>
      <li><strong>ML-DSA-44</strong> when signature size matters
          (constrained clients, cookie tokens) and Category 2 is acceptable
          for the application's threat horizon.</li>
      <li><strong>ML-DSA-87</strong> when a regulator or internal policy
          demands top-tier post-quantum strength (e.g. long-lived signed
          firmware images).</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-3">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">JOSE representation</h2>
    <p>jwt-pq uses the <code>AKP</code> key type from
      <code>draft-ietf-cose-dilithium</code>:</p>
    <pre class="bg-slate-50 p-4 rounded text-sm overflow-auto"><code class="language-json">{
  "kty": "AKP",
  "alg": "ML-DSA-65",
  "pub": "base64url(public_key_bytes)",
  "kid": "base64url(RFC 7638 thumbprint)"
}</code></pre>
    <p class="text-sm text-slate-600">
      Private JWKs add a <code>priv</code> field in the same base64url shape.
      The <code>kid</code> is the RFC 7638 thumbprint over
      <code>{alg, kty, pub}</code> — deterministic and independent of the
      private key.
    </p>
  </section>
</section>
